Introduction


Oh no, Papa Smurf has lost part of the standard library! He needs you to re-implement part of it in order to be able to keep an eye on all the smurfs, and without a proper linked list, he has no way to remember how many smurfs there are in the village.
In this practical, you will be working a lot with indexers, and basic to more advanced (for the bravest of you all) data structures.
You will be fairly guided throughout the practical, however, bear in mind that since you are being asked to implement well-known data structures, you may find lots of answers online, so don't forget, Google is your friend.
The notions you will see in this practical will be useful for the rest of your EPITA journey, but also further on as data structures never gets old.

This first part will require you to implement a simple linked list ... or maybe not ?!??
You will rather be implementing a double linked list.
A double linked list is a linked list where each cell has a reference to the next cell (as it is a linked list), and each cell has a reference to the previous cell (hence double linked list).
You will be asked to implement some functions and indexers to build a proper double linked list.

This class will represent a basic smurf, with its name, its age, and its money in smurf currency (yes the smurf used to have currency at some point).

SmurfList/SmurfList.cs


This file will contain all the required implementation for the double linked list.
Since we will be using cells, an inner class will be required with links to previous and next.
This class will contain all the methods and the inner class for the cell. This class will be implemented as the fundamentals go on.
The inner class used as cell within the SmurfList, this class will contain an object representing the value.

Information
This class is an inner class inside SmurfList class. An inner class is a class declared within another class. It can be used to restrict the visibility of a class to its parent only disallowing external users from using and interacting with this class.
It is usually used to hide the implementation of a class to the user. In our case, the user doesn't care about the cell in the linked list but is only interested in the effective values in the cell, hence the inner class.

Prototype(s)
public class SmurfList
{
    public class Cell { }
}

Since Cell is an inner public class, there is no need to make the attributes private, as the class in itself cannot exceed the bounds of SmurfList.
Therefore, we can allow ourselves to let all the attributes public, as it will ease the work later.
This class have 3 attributes:
  • object and named Value. It will hold the value of the cell. The case where Value is null will not be tested
  • Next and Prev will store respectively the next and the previous element in the list of type Cell?.
    Next and Prev are nullable, because, if they are respectively the last, or the first element, it will store nothing to mark the end or the beginging.

Information
The object is the root object that every class inherits from (including primitive types). Therefore, any value can be put in a variable of type object, which allows some kind of polymorphism in the objects within our cell.

The constructor for the Cell class takes only one parameter of type object for the value. However, you are free to add other constructors. Next and Prev should be null.

Prototype(s)
public Cell(object value) { }

Code example(s)
Cell c = new Cell('S');
// c.value = 'S'

You want to override the default ToString() method, to return what the method this.value.ToString() returns.

Prototype(s)
public override string ToString() {}

Code example(s)

// 'S'

Output
'S'

The SmurfList will require a current head (the first cell of the current linked list), and for end insert performances, we will be keeping track of the tail (the last cell of the linked list).
So the SmurfList will have 2 attributes:
  • A protected Cell? Head. It will be the first element of the list. And must be null if the list is empty.
  • A protected Cell? Tail. It will be the last element of the list. As same as head, it will be null if the list is empty
And 1 property:
  • An int Size with public getter and setter. To keep track the size.

Warning(s)
Note that the Head and the Tail were explicitly marked as possibly nullable. You will have to deal with that when working with empty lists.

You have to implement an empty constructor for the linked list doing nothing. Obviously, an empty class must have Size set to 0, a Head and Tail set to null.

Warning(s)
You must follow the previous listed conditions.

Prototype(s)
public SmurfList() { }

Code example(s)

// sl.Size == 0
// sl.Head == null
// sl.Tail == null

You have to implement a copy constructor that copy from the parameter smurfList, the properties Size, Head, and Tail.

Warning(s)
You must follow the previous listed conditions.
You must not re-create all cells, you only need to copy the properties.

Information
We are here asking for a *shallow* copy as opposed to a *deep* copy. A *shallow* copy consists in copying the _references_ of the fields into a new object whereas a *deep* copy consists in copying the _values_ of the fields recursively into a new object.
Therefore, a *shallow* copy is way faster than a *deep* copy but the copied objects share the same fields whereas a *deep* copy is much slower but has different fields with same values. You can look up more about it here.

Prototype(s)
public SmurfList(SmurfList smurfList) { }

Code example(s)
SmurfList sl = new SmurfList();
// sl.Size == 0
// sl.Head == null
// sl.Tail == null
SmurfList sl_copy = new SmurfList(sl);
// sl_copy.Size == 0
// sl_copy.Head == null
// sl_copy.Tail == null

In this part you will be implementing a hash map. A hash map resemble to a dictionary. It has keys and associated values. To store those associations, we calculate a hash of the key (it's operations that transform a complex data into a sequence of characters). This hash of the key represent the effective index in our internal array. In our case, the hash (so the index in our internal array) should be calculated using the hash code of the key modulo the size of the array. You can get the hash code of a key using inherited method Object.GetHashCode.


SmurfMap/IMapKey.cs


This interface will represent a key in the map, and it will extend the builtin interface IComparable<IMapKey>. Since this interface extends the IComparable interface, all classes that implements IMapKey must define a method CompareTo that will compare two objects. Don't worry, we'll come back on this method when needed.

Prototype(s)

Otherwise, compare the strings character by character.
If at any point the character of the current key and the character of the other key differs, return the difference between those two characters (e.g. _value[i] - other._value[i] where other is the argument of CompareTo).

// Compute the difference between 'a' and 'a'
// a = a => next char
// end of one of the two string =>
// return len("ab") - len("a") => 1

Code example(s)

// Difference between 'h' and 'h'
// 'h' = 'h' => charactere suivant
// End of string, compute the
// difference in lengths
// return len("h") - len("h") => 0

This method should grow the size of the array to a new size and put all the cells at their re-calculated indicies.
This method basically re-creates a new array and inserts all the elements from the previous array into the new array.
If the newSize is lower or equal to the current size, raise an ArgumentException.

Prototype(s)

Add a public getter of type SmurfList which returns a list containing all the keys of the hash map ordered as in the array.

Prototype(s)

Implement an indexer with a getter and a setter such that returning an object? and taking an IMapKey as parameter:
  • The getter throws a KeyNotFoundException if the key does not exist.
  • The getter returns the value corresponding to the given key.
  • If a key does not exists, the setter inserts the value.
  • If a key does exist, the setter replaces the value at Key.
When inserting, you must use the following algorithm:
  1. Check if the key exists already. If it does, replace the value and quit.
  2. Compute the index using the hash code (see formula above).
  3. Check the cell at the given index.
    If empty, put a MapCell at the given index.
    Else, find the first available cell in the array.
  4. If the array is more or exactly 75% filled, Grow the
    array to _values.Length * 2

Prototype(s)

Papa smurf now as a list of smurfs.
However, he would like to know some statistics about the population like what's the average money of the 10% richest/poorest, what's the average age of the 25% oldest? Of the 50% in the middle?
He knows he could, for each statistics recalculate everything from the population, but he would like to reduce the number of calculations whilst being able to get complex statistics over a given range.
In this part, you will be using Segment Trees. Segment Trees is a data structure based of a binary tree that allows to compute once some function for multiple pre-defined ranges in a list.
A segment tree is a tree that stores the results of the computation over multiple ranges (a segment) on data. The goal of a segment tree is to drastically reduce computations of a given operation over a range of data.
To build a segment tree, you need some data to work on, and an operation to apply to this data. Then you need the result of the calculation over the whole data as the root of the tree. You then split the data in the middle and apply the operation over the left part (whose result become the left child), and over the right part (whose result becomre the right child). And you perform this operation recursively such that the leafs contain the calculation for a single element in the initial list, and a parent contains the result of the computation over the range starting from the lower bound of the left child to the higher bound of the right child.
You are highly encouraged to read more about them here and here
Once again, you will be using mostly indexers in this part.


SmurfList/SmurfTree.cs


As explained above, the file will contain your implementation of Segment Trees called SmurfTree. Since it is a tree, it is a recursive data structure.

This class will have an input type, representing the type of data at each leaf.
This input type will be of type object to allow use of segment trees with any kind of object.
The output type will represent the result of whatever calculation on the range of input type.
In our case, we will be using int.

Prototype(s)
public class SmurfTree { }

Since it is a binary tree, it shall have at least a nullable reference to a left and right child.
Furthermore, since each node of the tree represents the result of the required calculation over a given range, the node should store the range is has data over.
Finally, we need two functions.
The first one that converts the input type to the output type for the leafs (the initiator)
The other one that merges the value of 2 sub ranges into a new one allowing merging all leafs into proper ranges when building and updating the tree (the _merger).

Prototype(s)
private SmurfTree? _left;  // the left child
private SmurfTree? _right; // the right child

private int _leftIndex;   // the begining included of the range
private int _rightIndex;     // the end excluded of the range
private int _value;        // the result of the computation
                          // on the range

private Func<object, int> _initiator;  // the initiator function
private Func<int, int, int> _merger;   // the merger function

Warning(s)
For the rest of the section, remember that _leftIndex is included and _rightIndex is excluded.
Keep this in mind to avoid counting same data multiple times.

The SmurfTree will feature one public constructor, taking an _initiator function, a merger function, and a list containing the data to build the tree from. This constructor should raise an ArgumentException in case the list is empty.
In case a segment you are building has an odd number of elements, the element in the middle should be in the right child and not the left child.

Warning(s)
We highly advise you to create a second private constructor that takes the begining and the end of the range to create more easily the children without duplicating the list.

Prototype(s)
public SmurfTree(Func<object, int> initiator, Func<int, int, int> merger, SmurfList input) { }

Code example(s)
SmurfList list = new SmurfList();
list.AppendAll(new object[]{ 1, 2, 3, 4 });
var tree = new SmurfTree(x => (int)x, (x, y) => x + y, list);
tree.Display();

Warning(s)
The Display method is to be implemented just after.

You are required to create a display function compatible with the mermaid markup language. You can check above some examples. You can find a link to the mermaid documentation here. Here are a few requirements for your mermaid code to be valid:
  • The display must start with the line flowchart TD
  • Each node must declare a subgraph.
  • The name of the subgraph must be sub_{number}
    where number is the number of the node such
    that:
    • The number of the root is 1
    • The number of the left child of a node is 2 * n + 1 where n is the number of the parent.
    • The number of the right child of a node is 2 * n + 2 where n is the number of the parent.
  • Each subgraph must be labelled with the range it covers
  • At the beginning of each non-leaf subgraph, add the direction TD directive so that the image render goes from bottom to top.
  • Each node must be labelled with the value of the range corresponding to the subgraph.
  • Each subgraph must be closed with end instruction
  • When displaying a child, an additional indent should be added for the display of the child. This indent is expected to be recursive when going down on the next child.

Prototype(s)
public void Display() { }

Code example(s)
SmurfList list = new SmurfList();
list.AppendAll(new object[]{ 1 });
var tree = new SmurfTree(x => (int)x, (x, y) => x + y, list);
tree.Display();

Information
You can play around with the mermaid language online.

                    // labelled 1, the value the range 0 covers in
                    // the corresponding subgraph

                                      // [0, 3[ where 0 is included, and 3 excluded.

        direction TB                  // sets the direction of the render from top to bottom

        node_1[6] --> sub_3           // creates the node corresponding to the subgraph
                                      // sub_1 called node_1, labelled 6 which is the
                                      // sum of values over the range [0, 3[
                                      // and binds this node to the subgraph sub_3

        subgraph sub_3[0]             // first child subgraph
                                      // labelled 0, which is the range it covers

                node_3["1"]           // creates the node corresponding to the subgraph
                                      // sub_3 called node_3 labelled 1
                                      // which is the value at index 0

        end                           // end instruction of subgraph sub_3

        node_1[6] --> sub_4           // bind root node node_1 to
                                      // subgraph sub_4

        subgraph sub_4["[1, 3["]      // creates the subgraph sub_4
                                      // covering the range [1, 3[

                direction TB          // direction directive

                node_4[5] --> sub_9   // creates node_4 corresponding to sub_4
                                      // labelled with the value of the range
                                      // [1, 3[, which is 5
                                      // and binds it to subgraph sub_9

                subgraph sub_9[1]     // creates leaf subgraph sub_9
                                      // covering the value 1 only

                        node_9["2"]   // creates the leaf node node_9 corresponding
                                      // to subgraph sub_9 labelled 2, which is
                                      // the value at index 1

                end                   // end directive for subgraph sub_9

                node_4[5] --> sub_10  // binds node_4 to subgraph sub_10

                subgraph sub_10[2]    // creates subgraph sub_10 over the index 2

                        node_10["3"]  // creates the corresponding node node_10
                                      // with value 3

                end                   // end directive for sub_10

        end                           // end directive for sub_4

end                                   // end directive for sub_1

A functions that checks whether a SmurfTree is a leaf or not.

Prototype(s)
public bool IsLeaf() { }

Hint(s)
A leaf is a node that has no child.

Your SmurfTree should be working properly right now.
However, if the list changes, how can you update the tree without having to rebuild it fully ?
We will now implement an indexer that will allow to modify a value in the tree.

Prototype(s)
public object this[int index] { }

This function should contain only a setter, and raise an IndexOutOfRangeException if the provided index is not valid.

Hint(s)
In the context of a Segment Tree, the end index of the root is not a valid index, since you cannot modify the length of the underlying list as it would break the correct split of the tree.

Warning(s)
You should only modify the value of the leaf at index and use the merger function to update all the parents of this leaf.

Code example(s)
SmurfList list = new SmurfList();
list.AppendAll(new object[]{1, 2, 3, 4});
SmurfTree tree = new SmurfTree(x => (int)x, (x, y) => x + y, list);
tree[3] = 42;

Here is an image of the tree before and after the set
of the value 42 at the index 3.





Now we would like an indexer that computes the result of
the merge of all the data in a given range.

Prototype(s)
public int this[int start, int end] { }

This indexer should only feature a getter returning the sum
of all value between start included, and end excluded.
if one of the two indices is invalid, raise an
IndexOutOfRangeException.
if start >= end, raise ArgumentException

Code example(s)
SmurfList list = new SmurfList();
list.AppendAll(new object[]{ 1, 2, 3 });
SmurfTree tree = new SmurfTree(x => (int)x, (x, y) => x + y, list);
Console.WriteLine(tree[0, 3]);  // 6
Console.WriteLine(tree[1, 3]);  // 5
Console.WriteLine(tree[3, 1]);  // ArgumentException
Console.WriteLine(tree[10, 1]); // ArgumentException
Console.WriteLine(tree[1, 10]); // IndexOutOfRangeException
Console.WriteLine(tree[0, 0]);  // ArgumentException
Console.WriteLine(tree[0, 1]);  // 1

Output
6
5

SmurfControl/MovingWindow.cs


This class that will be abstract will allow you to use the Segment trees implemented earlier to perform all sorts of computation over a given range.

Prototype(s)
public abstract class MovingWindow { }

Moving window will have a private int named _length that will hold the range length of the moving window.

The moving window will have a protected SmurfTree called Tree with private setter and protected getter.
It will also have a public property called Length with public getter returning the attribute _length and a public setter setting the attribute _length if the value is stricly positive.
Otherwise, raise an ArgumentException

The constructor of the moving window. It sets all the properties to their corresponding value.

Prototype(s)
public MovingWindow(SmurfTree tree, int initialLen) { }

You will now be implementing an abstract indexer with getter only returning an int, and taking an int as the index to calculate the range from.
This indexer will be implemented in subclasses to perform specific calculations over the range index included to index + Length excluded.

Prototype(s)
public abstract int this[int index] { }


SmurfControl/MeanMovingWindow.cs


This class will extend the MovingWindow abstract class. You should be implementing the default constructor respecting the parent constructor prototype and call the base constructor in your MeanMovingWindow constructor.

Prototype(s)
public class MeanMovingWindow { }

Prototype(s)
public MeanMovingWindow(SmurfTree tree, int initialLen) { }

This indexer should return the mean of the data contained in Tree over the range
[index, index + Length[
where index is the parameter of the indexer.
It should raise an IndexOutOfRangeException if the range is invalid.

Hint(s)
If the range is invalid, the SmurfTree already raises an IndexOutOfRangeException

Code example(s)
SmurfList list = new SmurfList();
list.AppendAll(new object[]{1, 2, 3, 4});
SmurfTree tree = new SmurfTree(x => (int)x, (x, y) => x + y, list);
MovingWindow mean = new MeanMovingWindow(tree, 2);
Console.WriteLine(mean[2]);   // 3
mean.Length = 4;
Console.WriteLine(mean[0]);   // 2

Output
3
2


SmurfControl/MedianMovingWindow.cs


This class will extend the MovingWindow abstract class.
You should be implementing the default constructor respecting the parent constructor prototype and call the base constructor in your MeanMovingWindow constructor.

Prototype(s)
public class MedianMovingWindow { }

Prototype(s)
public MedianMovingWindow(SmurfTree tree, int initialLen) { }

This indexer should return the median of the data contained in Tree over the range
[index, index + Length[
where index is the parameter of the indexer. That is the value at the index index + (Length / 2). It should raise an IndexOutOfRangeException if the range is invalid.

Hint(s)
If the range is invalid, the SmurfTree already raises an IndexOutOfRangeException

Code example(s)
SmurfList list = new SmurfList();
list.AppendAll(new object[]{1, 2, 3, 4});
SmurfTree tree = new SmurfTree(x => (int)x, (x, y) => x + y, list);
MovingWindow median = new MedianMovingWindow(tree, 2);
Console.WriteLine(median[2]); // 4
median.Length = 3;
Console.WriteLine(median[1]); // 3
Console.WriteLine(median[3]); // IndexOutOfRangeException

Output
4
3
